# TripSync (CSEN 174) — team repository

## Scope
- Respect each teammate’s divergent prototype under `prototypes/<name>/`.
- Prefer small, focused changes; avoid unrelated drive-by refactors.

## Secrets
- Never commit `.env` or API keys. Use `*.env.example` and document variables in the prototype README.

## Prototype
- GP Hora app: `prototypes/gurprasaadhora/tripsync` (Vite + React, Express + SQLite + Groq). Align feature ideas with `product-vision.md` when the team updates it.
# Orbit - AI-Powered Interactive Travel Guide

## Product Vision
See `product-vision.md` for the full product vision statement.

## Architecture
See `architecture/architecture.md` for the system architecture, consolidation plan, and C4 diagrams (Mermaid).

## Project Overview
Orbit is an AI-powered travel companion that surfaces nearby points of interest and delivers real-time, audio-based tour guide experiences. Unlike static map apps, Orbit adapts to the user's location and interests to proactively surface relevant places and provide conversational, context-aware insights.

## Repository Structure
- `product-vision.md` — Shared product vision (Moore's template)
- `prototypes/` — Individual prototype directories per team member
  - Each prototype is independent and may use a different tech stack
  - Each has its own `.env.example` documenting required environment variables
- `.cursor/skills/` — Cursor skills for storyboarding, frontend design, etc.

## Conventions
- Never commit `.env` files or API keys
- Each prototype lives in `prototypes/<name>/` with its own dependencies
- Prefer clear, conversational UI copy that matches Orbit's friendly tone
- Audio-first interaction patterns are a core product differentiator
